"were judged to be “extremely handsome and roomy vehicles,” the first class being ‘‘luxuriously” fitted up, and the third declared to be incomparably superior to those of any other railway in the land. Moreover, they were lit by gas instead of oil-lamps, the gas being carried in long india-rubber bags covering the roof of each carriage. In this respect, also, the Metropolitan was a pioneer, and passengers were said to find the carriages so bright as utterly to remove all sense of travelling underground. But sixty years ago the public was not so blasé as it is to-day, and gave a more rapturous welcome to each new improvement. The first train service was run on broad-gauge lines, and it was worked for a few weeks by the Great Western Railway, but a little later narrow gauge rails were added, and for many years both continued in use, as may be seen in one of the illustrations."